"Collaborative research was wonderful - something we historians rarely do."

What an inspiring afternoon at NIAS for the #PaperlessWorkshop and presentation of the book 'Empire‚Äôs Violent End'. The workshop and the book are both outputs of NIAS Theme Group 2018/19 ‚ÄúComparing the wars of decolonization: Extreme violence during reoccupation and counter-insurgency, 1945-1975‚Äù. 

Today a first edition of the book was presented to NIAS Director Jan Willem Duyvendak. Along with the above comment another Editor noted that the "Collaborative intellectual exchange within the chapters is remarkable". 

We are very proud of our alumni and the members of the theme group: Dr. Thijs Zaalberg Brocades and Dr. Bart Luttikhuis, Dr. Pierre Asselin and Dr. Esther Captain, Brian McAllister Linn and Azarja Harmanny, Dr. Natalya Vince and Dr. Stef Scagliola, Dr. Huw Bennett and Professor Peter Romijn, and Professor Martin Thomas and Dr. Roel Frakking. 

Congratulations to everyone involved for your hardwork! Thanks for coming back to NIAS to host this innovative workshop and for sharing this success with us. 

Empire's Violent End is available from Athenaeum Boekhandel.

The province of Davao de Oro has been declared free from armed communist insurgency, the Philippine Army (PA) reported on Thursday.

The military and the local government of Davao de Oro made the declaration during a ceremony held at the Provincial Capitol Grounds, in Barangay Cabidianan, Nabunturan town on Wednesday.

It was attended by National Security Adviser Hermogenes Esperon Jr., incoming Department of National Defense officer-in-charge Jose Faustino Jr., and other key officials.

Edinburgh ‚Äì Glasgow via Falkirk High: two trains per hour
Edinburgh ‚Äì Bathgate: two trains per hour
Glasgow ‚Äì Hamilton/Larkhall: two trains per hour

We highly recommend arranging alternative transport or finding pals to stay with for the night if you plan on coming to this show. Any and all attendance will be greatly appreciated, particularly considering what the journey will look like now.

The Siege Of Mecca (Grand Mosque Seizure) | 1979, Saudi Arabia

During a period of two weeks between November and December 1979, extrem1st insurgents took over the holiest mosque in Islam ‚Äî the Masjid al-Haram ‚Äî in Mecca, Saudi Arabia. These insurgents claimed that the Mahdi (the redeemer of Islam) had come to Earth in the form of one of the group‚Äôs leaders (Mohammed Abudallah Al-Qatani).

Juhayman Al-Otaybi (fifth slide) was the principal leader of the insurgency after Al-Qatani was killed during the siege. Al-Otaybi‚Äôs ancestors were closely linked to the Al-Saud dynasty, yet Juhayman‚Äôs goals were fuelled by what he perceived as the loss of legitimacy of the Al Saud dynasty ‚Äúbecause it was corrupt, ostentatious and had destroyed Saudi culture by an aggressive policy of Westernisation.‚Äù

The siege led to the deaths of hundreds of militants, security forces, as well as hostages taken by the insurgents. After a continuous period of fighting which lasted two weeks, the Saudi Army (advised by the French GIGN) reclaimed the Grand Mosque. The 67 remaining insurgents (one of which was Al-Otaybi) were captured and beheaded. A period of reinforced religious conservatism ensued alongside the increase of power given to the religious police.

Today in 1948 the Malayan emergency üö® began when members of the Malaysian communist party shot and killed 3 European plantation owners. A state of emergency was declared shortly after and soon a major insurgency had begun. 

Malaysia üá≤üáæ at this point was still a part of British empire and wasn‚Äôt one colony but several, Malaya is the part bordering Thailand üáπüá≠. The Malaysia communist party was actually mostly made up of Chinese who made up around 30% of the population and tensions the Malays were high. The communist formed the Malayan National Liberation Army (MNLA) who‚Äôs goal was force the British out of Malaya and make it a communist nation.

Establishing bases deep in jungle the MNLA instituted guerrilla warfare against the British, launching raids against outposts, towns, and industrial areas. Most Malays were pro-British and the British were reinforced by forces from all over the commonwealth. When Malaya declared independence as the Federation of Malaya in 1957 the MNLA lost its reason for existing and support for it collapsed. The emergency was declared over in 1960. 

The Federation of Malaya would join with Britain‚Äôs other former southeast Asian colonies (except Brunei üáßüá≥) to form the present day Malaysia üá≤üáæ we know today, (although Singapore üá∏üá¨ would later be kicked out).

‚ÄúThe three conditions that must be present for an insurgency to develop are opportunity, motive, and means.
Opportunity alludes to the emergence of significant gaps in the ability of the national government or local allies to provide security for its territory and population.
There should be a compelling motive to organize an insurgency, because insurgents are generally treated as violent, traitorous criminals by the security forces, government authorities, and potentially some segments of the indigenous population.
For means, the leaders of emerging insurgencies will covertly establish systems that allow them to procure, assemble, and organize personnel, funds, weapons, secure communications, and logistics‚Ä¶

In many operations, the defeat of the enemy‚Äôs military capabilities is the main focus of JIPOE [joint intelligence preparation of the operational environment]. COIN, however, is focused on the threat (insurgents, terrorists, criminals, and their direct support), indigenous population (often representing the neutral network), and friendly forces (part of the friendly network) in the context of mitigating conditions that are driving or enabling a continuing insurgency.‚Äù
~Counterinsurgency, US Military Field Manual 3-24, US Joint Chiefs of Staff

In our podcast with Brum Richards out this week we discuss operations in Aden and the Radfan which he took part in. 

During the early 1960s the Cold War reached its climax. Britain's dwindling power in the Middle East was under siege from Arab nationalism, the Communist bloc and from American designs in the region. Aden, with its strategic military base and old Protectorate buffer zone, was soon the main battleground.

 The 1962 Egyptian-inspired coup in the neighbouring Kingdom of North Yemen further tightened the noose. So began a bitter and bloody insurgency war in South Arabia. British regular and special forces were soon pitted against growing and formidable insurgency forces, fighting both a war in the mountains and an urban conflict in the backstreets of Aden. 

Intelligence agencies vied for control of 'hearts and minds'. The British launched a clandestine war in Yemen to keep their enemies at bay. But still the situation in Aden spiralled out of control before the British withdrew at the end of 1967.
